<PROFILE>_AN-DATCPABTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930120
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: PM scorns utilities' windfall tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S plan for a windfall tax on privatised utilities was brushed off by
Mr John Major yesterday as a product of the 'anti-business' thinking of the
1960s and 1970s, Philip Stephens writes.
But as the gas, telephone, water and electricity companies escape the chill
of the recession, Labour believes its proposal to claw back their 'excess'
profits will strike a chord with the electorate.
The plan - presented yesterday by Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor -
starts from the premise that the regulatory authorities have been
ineffectual in holding the profits of the utilities to a sensible level.
Mr Brown drew a parallel with the windfall tax imposed on the banks by the
Conservative government in 1981. Lord Howe, who was then chancellor, judged
that the banks had been unfairly shielded from the impact of the early 1980s
recession.
The cumulative profits of the utilities in the four years to 1992-93 will
amount to more than Pounds 35bn, Labour estimates. Since 1989-90 they will
have jumped by 70 per cent to Pounds 10.5bn a year.
That contrasts with a severe squeeze on most corporate profits. Labour
concludes that the utilities have been unfairly cushioned by their pricing
structures and by the monopoly nature of their markets.
The party's calculations suggest that rates of return running at 11 per cent
or so for the water companies and at over 20 per cent for British Telecom
are out of line with the risk faced by the industries and with their
investment needs. Mr Brown will not put a figure on the 'excess', but one
suggestion is that it ranges from a minimum of Pounds 500m to perhaps as
much as Pounds 2.5bn.
Mr Major stressed that the regulatory authorities could curb 'excess'
profits by forcing lower prices, as in the case of British Telecom.
But Mr Brown judges that the initial popularity of the privatised utilities
has given way to resentment at their profits. He may have made also a
blunter assessment: it is easier to propose taxing BT's profits than to
suggest raising income tax.
</TEXT>
