<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major hints at benefit changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday hinted that changes to social security rules aimed
at helping the unemployed might be included in the Budget, David Owen
writes.
With pressure for a large-scale jobs package set to mount in the wake of
tomorrow's monthly unemployment figures, Mr Major described remarks made by
Mr Jeff Rooker, Labour MP for Birmingham Perry Barr, as 'well worth
considering'.
His comments came as Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, played down
the prospect of the wholesale adoption of Workfare - obliging people to work
in return for benefit - saying it was 'an extremely expensive solution' to
Britain's jobs difficulties.
Mrs Shephard said on BBC radio that the government needed 'a whole range of
measures which keep people in touch with the world of work, because it is
productive and gives them hope'. She said she remained 'open-minded' about
ways of keeping people 'in touch with the world of work'.
Workfare is one area under consideration by a cabinet committee recently set
up by Mr Major under Lord Wakeham, leader of the Lords, to suggest schemes
to tackle unemployment.
A report from Full Employment UK, a policy consultancy, is due to reach the
prime minister this week. It estimates that the cost of operating an
obligatory scheme to take 400,000 long-term unemployed off the dole queue
would be more than Pounds 630m.
Mr Rooker, a frontbench education spokesman, urged Mr Major to ease rules on
social security benefits so that unemployed people with 'household
responsibilities' could 'genuinely' take advantage of opportunities to
improve their education and training.
Accepting Mr Rooker's point was worth considering, the prime minister said:
'We have looked in the past at some matters related to that; these are the
sort of matters that we are prepared to examine.'
</TEXT>
