<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Councils win cash concession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL councils in England will be allowed to spend an extra Pounds 150m next
year above the government's original expenditure plans. The concession stems
mainly from a revision of how spending should take account of authorities'
losing responsibility for further education.
While the amount is relatively small compared with the overall planned
spending for local government in England of just over Pounds 41bn, it could
be critical in enabling some councils to escape the formal 'capping' process
through which the government limits local budgets.
Authorities benefiting most include Kent, which receives an increase of
Pounds 16.3m; Cheshire, with an increase of just over Pounds 12m; and
Nottinghamshire, up by almost Pounds 9m.
Altogether, 23 councils have received increases of more than Pounds 3m in
the amounts the government says they can spend. In London, the largest
increase is to Camden (Pounds 4.2m).
Mr John Redwood, local government minister, said yesterday that the changes
had been made on the basis of new and more accurate information.
The move follows about 200 representations to ministers from councils. When
the plans were first announced in November last year, local authorities
warned that the government's intended deduction of Pounds 2.4bn from local
spending to reflect the switch of further education was too much.
Ministers expect the main opposition attack to be over the level of
settlement rather than the nature of the council tax. They are hopeful,
however, that a significant proportion of threatened job losses in local
government will come from natural wastage.
</TEXT>
