FT  20 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lottery status divides MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CAMPAIGN to make the government change its proposals for a national
lottery and to give the organisation charitable status won backing from Tory
MPs yesterday.
Sir Ivan Lawrence, Conservative chairman of the home affairs select
committee, was among Tories who endorse the National Lottery Campaign. The
campaigners argue that charitable status will make the national lottery
independent of government and ensure its exemption from taxation.
The Department of Heritage argues that there would be no benefits from
charitable status.
The campaign was accompanied by signs of friction among Labour MPs, who were
concerned to oppose the lottery proposals. About 110 Labour MPs have written
to Mr John Smith, Labour leader, calling on the opposition party to oppose
the national lottery bill when it is debated in the Commons on Monday.
The letter says the national lottery will affect jobs in the football pools
industry and that 'there can be legitimate principled reasons for objecting
to raising revenue through government-sponsored gambling.' The letter also
says local charities may be affected,
However, Mr Austin Mitchell, Labour MP for Great Grimsby, supported the
National Lottery Campaign. 'People are going to be more enthusiastic about
buying tickets if the money is going into charitable purposes, rather than
being siphoned off by the Treasury,' he said.
</TEXT>
