<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 93 / World Trade News: End Gatt talks, says Dunkel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNLESS the Uruguay Round of trade liberalising talks is concluded quickly it
could founder, Mr Arthur Dunkel, Gatt director-general, warned yesterday. He
told the Trade Negotiations Committee (TNC), which oversees the 112-nation
round, that the talks were 'poised for conclusion'. 'We are critically short
of time. We must conclude now or risk drifting into the sands.'
The meeting was called to review progress in the six-year-old talks on the
eve of President Clinton's inauguration today. It follows two weeks'
intensive US-EC tariff negotiations which failed to produce breakthroughs.
In an appeal to the new administration to conclude a Uruguay Round deal
before the negotiating mandate granted by Congress expires in March, Mr
Dunkel said it 'can, and must be, concluded quickly'. He saw 'growing fears
that a long delay would cause a dangerous loss of momentum' where even the
existing trading system could be put at risk. Frustration was growing that
the biggest traders had not provided end-game leadership.
Since December, the Round has focused on tariff cuts, initial commitments to
liberalise services and possible changes to the draft package of rules known
as the 'final act', drawn up by Mr Dunkel in December 1991. He said
yesterday that most nations were willing to live with the draft final act in
its present form 'in the interest of a quick conclusion', repeating that
changes to the draft could only be by consensus.
The strongest objections to the draft final act have come from Japan and
South Korea over proposals to open their rice markets; Canada and others
which would have to scrap farm supply management systems; India over the
textiles accord; and the US over issues including creation of a powerful
Multilateral Trade Organisation.
Mr Hugo Paemen, EC chief negotiator, said Brussels was committed to a rapid
end of the round 'within its present parameters'. This reflects fears that
if Mr Clinton needs a fresh negotiating mandate new issues will be put on
the agenda, delaying the talks further and risking agreements made in
principle.
Colombia, Costa Rica and Guatemala yesterday said they would veto any Round
accord if the EC did not change its proposed regime for Latin American
banana imports. The EC plan, applying punitive tariffs to 'dollar' bananas
above a 2m-ton annual quota, could cut imports from Latin America 30 per
cent, they said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
