<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 93 / World Trade News: Kantor voices fears on US-EC farm deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Mickey Kantor, nominee for US trade representative in the Clinton
administration, yesterday expressed 'concern' about the US-EC agreement over
farm trade, sealed by his predecessor in an effort to push the Uruguay Round
to a conclusion.
Just a few minutes into his nomination hearing before the Senate finance
committee the California lawyer swept away concerns about his inexperience
in trade matters by politely correcting one senator on the details of the
US-EC farm trade deal. 'The devil is in the details,' he said. 'I think it
has to be looked at closely.'
Less than three hours later the finance committee approved Mr Kantor's
appointment, sending it on to the Senate for a full vote. Mr Kantor said he
hoped to be at work by tomorrow morning.
That was after he threw a new thunderbolt at the EC, insisting 'the US must
respond to the new utilities directive that went into effect on January 1'.
The local content requirements and preference given to local suppliers in
government procurement was 'a serious matter'.
Mr Kantor, a longtime Clinton friend, spoke with ease across the range of
issues he would have to deal with. He declined to commit himself on many
points, including the need to extend fast-track negotiating, hinting he
might consider working for a less ambitious package of reforms than the one
long stalled in the Uruguay Round.
He defined himself as 'a realistic person,' who would not simply assume
other countries supported the concept of free trade when the facts indicated
otherwise.
Perhaps without meaning to, Mr Kantor sent a subtle message of change in US
trade policy. When it has to act, the Clinton administration will be more
concerned with the reaction of the US voters than of its trading partners.
He promised to support a renewal of the controversial Super 301 provision,
which requires the US trade representative to single out countries with
excessive trade barriers for negotiation and perhaps retaliation.
'The days when we could afford to subordinate our economic interests to
foreign or defence concerns are long past,' he said. However, he added: 'No
amount of negotiating, bilaterally or multilaterally, can overcome or offset
the burdens placed on US companies from misguided economic policies or
uncontrolled health care costs. Nor are trade negotiations a substitute for
educating our children or training our workers.'
A 'coherent US economic strategy' will be co-ordinated within the new
national economic policy.
As trade representative, he will be the administration spokesman on trade,
and its negotiator. 'I will be the leader in that area,' he said,
emphasising: 'I will have direct access to the president.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  USA.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
