<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 93 / Debate on Bosnian peace plan adjourned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PALE, BOSNIA,, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bosnian Serb parliament last night adjourned a crucial debate on the
Geneva peace plan as a midnight deadline passed for acceptance of the
constitutional proposals for a new Bosnian state.
The debate, which is to resume this morning, took place as international
mediators Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen prepared to fly to Zagreb and
Sarajevo today.
The Bosnian Serb assembly, meeting in Pale, was to debate the proposed
framework, under which Bosnia would remain a unitary state, but would be
divided into 10 largely self-governing provinces.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, last week accepted the plan,
on condition that it was approved by his assembly, and after he had been
subjected to strong pressure by Mr Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian
president.
During a pause in last night's debate Mr Karadzic expressed confidence that
the measures would be approved. However the 7 1/2 -hour session included
many speeches from opponents.
Mr Fred Eckhard, the spokesman for Lord Owen and Mr Vance, said they had
been invited by President Alija Izetbegovic of Bosnia in an attempt to bring
an end to the flare-up of fighting between Moslems and Croats, nominally
allies in the conflict with the Serbs.
The two men will have talks with President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia and
Bosnian Croat leader Mr Mate Boban in Zagreb, after meeting Mr Izetbegovic
but will not go to Pale.
It is clear that the Bosnian Serbs interpret the peace proposals differently
from their authors, who see them as a guarantee against the creation of an
independent Serb state within Bosnia, which would have the freedom to decide
on a union with Serbia proper.
In Pale, Serb officials, in an attempt to justify their expected approval of
the constitutional framework, said they viewed it as similar to the UN peace
plan for Croatia: a means to consolidate their territorial gains in Bosnia.
Far from restoring Bosnia-Hercegovina's territorial integrity, the officials
said the plan opened the way to a de facto recognition of a Bosnian Serb
republic.
AP adds: 'The atrocities of the Croats and Bosnian Moslems pale in
comparison to the sheer scale and calculated cruelty of the killings and
other abuses committed by Serbian and Bosnian Serbian forces against Bosnian
Moslems,' the US State Department said yesterday in its annual human rights
report to Congress.
</TEXT>
