<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 93 / Industry price rises exert strains on inflation policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURERS IN the UK are pushing up prices in the wake of sterling's
devaluation, putting pressure on the government's anti-inflation strategy.
Downing Street said yesterday it was confident the government's inflation
target of between 1 and 4 per cent would be met, in spite of the spate of
price rises. But one senior minister said: 'It is the old story. Companies
seem to be throwing away their advantage, just when they should be strongly
placed for recovery.'
Price rises in the past few weeks include:
More than 7 per cent on electrical goods from Siemens UK;
8 per cent on float glass from Pilkington;
Up to 13 per cent on steel from British Steel;
Up to 7.5 per cent on Ford cars;
Up to 12.5 per cent on personal computers.
Mr John Major yesterday reiterated to MPs the importance he attaches to
reducing inflation, 'so we can create lasting jobs for the future'. Downing
Street also said it expected price rises to be offset by price falls
elsewhere.
Manufacturers in hard-pressed industries such as building materials and
chemicals expect no price increases until demand picks up. Ready-mixed
Concrete, the cement maker, said: 'First we have to stop them falling'.
However, importers of finished goods from the continent pointed out that
devaluation meant cost increases in sterling terms of 15 per cent.
The government had hoped that manufacturers would respond to devaluation by
freezing prices and pushing up market share against imports, thus helping
the balance of payments. However, Pilkington and British Steel have been
losing money.
It is not yet clear that all the mooted price rises will take effect.
Pilkington and British Steel have tried to raise prices without success in
the past few years. In glass, steel and personal computers prices have
actually fallen sharply.
In cars, it is not yet clear whether the latest price rises will be whittled
away by discounts. However, the latest price rises from Ford come hard on
the heels of a rise in October last year. Prices were also raised late last
year by Rover and Vauxhall.
Analysts said that industrial price increases could leave some companies
exposed if the French franc were also forced to devalue. In addition, the
deepening recession in continental Europe continues to push prices down in
some products, thus offsetting the effects of devaluation for companies
exporting to the UK.
For the government, the dilemma is that if price increases fail to stick, it
will be principally because the UK economy is not recovering as fast as
companies hoped. In that case, industry's behaviour to date suggests that
inflationary pressures will merely be postponed until recovery arrives.
Recovery gamble, Page 8
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99  Nonclassifiable Establishments.
    P9611  Administration of General Economic Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
